L1

What Is Statistical Learning?

  • Example

X→input : predictor, indep. variable ,feature var.
Y→output: response, dep. variable

  • Quantitative response \(Y\) and \(p\) different predictors \(X_1,...,X_p\) \[Y=f(X)+\epsilon\]

\(X \sim i.i.d,E(\epsilon)=0\) Thus, we want estimate \(f\) methods.

Linear Regression

Simple Linear Regression

It assumes that there is approximately a linear relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\). Mathematically, we can write this linear relationship as

\[Y = \beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X+\epsilon\] or
\[Y \approx \beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X\]

\(\beta_{0}\)and \(\beta_{1}\)are two unknown constants that represent the intercept and slope terms in the linear model. We have used our training data to produce estimates \(\hat\beta_{0}\)and \(\hat\beta_{1}\)for the model coefficients. \[\hat Y = \hat\beta_{0}+\hat\beta_{1}X\]

  • OLS doesn’t need to prob. assumption and distribution.

  • MLE needs.

  • Estimating the Coefficients

\(\hat Y_i = \hat\beta_{0}+\hat\beta_{1}X_i\) be the prediction for \(Y\) based on the \(i\)th value of \(X\). Then \(e_i=y_i-\hat y_i\)represents the \(i\)th residual—this is the difference between the \(i\)th observed response value and the \(i\)th response value that is predicted by our linear model. We define the \(residual \ sum \ of \ squares\) (\(\color{blue}{\text{RSS}}\)) as

\[RSS = e^2_1+...+e^2_n\]

The least squares approach chooses\(\hat\beta_0\) and \(\hat\beta_1\)to minimize the RSS. Using some calculus, one can show that the minimizers are \[\hat\beta_1 = \frac{ \sum_ {i=1}^{n} {(x_i-\bar{X})(y_i-\bar{Y})}}{\sum_ {i=1}^{n} {(x_i-\bar{X})^2}}\]
\[\hat\beta_0 = \bar y - \hat\beta_1 \bar X\]

  • Assessing the Accuracy of the Coefficient Estimates:
  1. About \(\mu\) (the population mean of \(Y\)), In general, \(\sigma^2\) is not known. It is estimated by residual standard error (RSE) and is given by the formula \(RSE=\sqrt{RSS / (n-2)}.\)
  2. About \(\hat\beta_0\), \(SE(\hat\beta_0)=\sigma^2\{\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\bar X^2}{\sum_ {i=1}^{n} {(x_i-\bar{X})^2}}\}\)
    the 95% confidence interval for \(\hat\beta_0\) approximately takes the form \(\hat\beta_0 \pm 1.96 \times SE(\hat\beta_0)\)
  3. About \(\hat\beta_1\), \(SE(\hat\beta_1)=\frac{\sigma^2}{\sum_ {i=1}^{n} {(x_i-\bar{X})^2}}\)
    the 95% confidence interval for \(\hat\beta_1\) approximately takes the form \(\hat\beta_1 \pm 1.96 \times SE(\hat\beta_1)\)

\(H_0 : There \ is \ no \ relationship \ between \ X \ and \ Y \ \beta_1 \neq 0\)
\(versus\)
\(H_a : There \ is \ some \ relationship \ between \ X \ and \ Y . \beta_1 = 0\)
Mathematically, this corresponds to testing

T-test:
\[t=\frac{\hat\beta_1-0}{SE(\hat\beta_1)},df=2\] * Assessing the Accuracy of the Model:
1. RSE
2. \(R^2\) Statistics: \(\frac{TSS-RSS}{TSS}=1-\frac{RSS}{TSS}\)where \(TSS = \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\bar Y)^2\)
3. adj \(R^2 = (1-R^2)\frac{n-1}{n-p-1}\),\(p\) is the number of predictors \(|t|>t_{0.05}=1.96(if \ n \geq30)\)

Multiple Linear Regression

  • Assumption: \[\hat Y = \hat\beta_{0}+\hat\beta_{1}X_1+...+\hat\beta_{p}X_p\]
  • Estimating the Coefficients: We choose \(\hat\beta_{0},...,\beta_{p}\) to minimize the sum of squared residuals:

\[min \ RSS = min \sum_{i=1}^{n} {(y_i-\hat y_i)^2}=min \sum_{i=1}^{n} {(y_i-\hat\beta_{0}-\hat\beta_{1}X_{i1}-...-\hat\beta_{p}X_{ip})^2}\]

  • Some Important Questions
  1. Is at least one of the predictors \(X_1,X_2, . . . , X_p\) useful in predicting the response?
    ◼ We test the null hypothesis,
    \(H_0 : β_1 = β_2 = · · · = β_p = 0\) versus \(H_a : at \ least \ one \ β_j \ is \ non-zero.\)
    This hypothesis test is performed by computing the F-statistic,

\[F=\frac{(RSS_0-RSS)/q}{RSS/(n-p-1)},df = (q,n-p-1), \ F>F_\alpha (p-value< \alpha)\]

\(H_1: full \ model,RSS_0,\beta_j=0,j=1,...,q (few \ variable,bigger \ RSS)\)

\(H_1: reduced \ model,RSS,\beta_j \neq0,j=1,...,q (more \ variable,smaller \ RSS)\)

if \(F>F_\alpha , \ reject H_0(choose \ the \ full \ model)\) if \(F\leq F_\alpha, \ accepct \ H_0 (choose \ the \ reduced \ model)\) 2. Do all the predictors help to explain Y , or is only a subset of the predictors useful?
◼ Forward,Backward model selection.
Don’t use stepwise
3. How well does the model fit the data?
◼ RSE, R square, adj R square,
4. Given a set of predictor values, what response value should we predict, and how accurate is our prediction?
◼ We can compute a determine how close \(\hat y\) will be to y.

L2

Classification I

Linear Regression vs. Classification

  • The linear regression model assumes that the response variable \(Y\) is quantitative. But in many situations, the response variable is instead quanlitative/categorical.

  • Three of the most widely-used classifiers:

  1. logistic regression (k=2)
  2. linear discriminant analysis (LDA) k$geq$2
  3. K-nearest neighbors (KNN)
    Other: Decision tree, QDA, Bayesian, Random forest

Logistic regression

  • Example:
    We have plotted annual income and monthly credit card balance for a subset of 10,000 individuals

\[Y={\begin{cases} \ {0}&{\text{,No (default)}}\\~~{1}&{\text{,Yes}}.\end{cases}}\]

names(Default)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
boxplot(balance~default,col=c("deepskyblue2","red3"))
boxplot(income~default,col=c("deepskyblue2","red3"))

  • Model:

    • For the data, logistic regression models the probability of default. For example, the probability of default given \(X\) can be written as
      \[{\displaystyle \operatorname Pr(Y=1|balance)=Pr(Y='Yes'|balance)=Pr(balance)={\begin{cases}\text{Yes}&{\text{,if }}>0.5\\{\text{No} }&{\text{,otherwise}}.\end{cases}}}\]

  • Using a linear regression model to represent these probabilities:
    \(P(X)=\beta_0+\beta X\) These predictions are not sensible, since the prob. Most fall between 0 to 1.

  • Taking log-odds or logit: \[{\displaystyle p(Y=1|X)={\frac {1}{1+e^{-(\beta_{0}+\beta _{1}x)}}}}\]

\[{\displaystyle {\frac {p(x)}{1-p(x)}}=e^{\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x}.}\]

\(log{\frac {p(x)}{1-p(x)}}\) range is between (\(-\infty\),\(\infty\))

  • Estimation the likelihood function:
    Consider a generalized linear model function parameterized by \({\displaystyle \theta }\),

\[{\displaystyle h_{\theta }(X)={\frac {1}{1+e^{-\theta ^{T}X}}}=\Pr(Y=1\mid X;\theta )}\]

Therefore,

\[{\displaystyle \Pr(Y=0\mid X;\theta )=1-h_{\theta }(X)}\]

and since \({\displaystyle Y\in \{0,1\}}\), we see that \({\displaystyle \Pr(y\mid X;\theta )}\) is given by \({\displaystyle \Pr(y\mid X;\theta )=h_{\theta }(X)^{y}(1-h_{\theta }(X))^{(1-y)}.}\) We now calculate the likelihood function assuming that all the observations in the sample are independently Bernoulli distributed, \[{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}L(\theta \mid y;x)&=\Pr(Y\mid X;\theta )\\&=\prod _{i}\Pr(y_{i}\mid x_{i};\theta )\\&=\prod _{i}h_{\theta }(x_{i})^{y_{i}}(1-h_{\theta }(x_{i}))^{(1-y_{i})}\end{aligned}}}\] To obtain \(\hat\beta_0,\hat\beta_1\):

\[l(\beta_0,\beta_1)=\prod _{i=1}^{n}P(x_{i})^{y_{i}}(1-P(x_{i}))^{(1-y_{i})}\] \(\hat\beta_0,\hat\beta_1\) are chosen to maximize \(l(\beta_0,\beta_1)\)

  • Making Prediction

  • Multiple Logistic regression

  • Multiple-Class (K>2)
    The two-class logistic regression models have multiple-class extensions, but in practice they tend not to be used all that often.

LDA

  • Why not using logistic regression

    • When there is \(\color{blue}{\text{well-separated}}\) between the two classes, the parameter estimates for the logistic regression model are surprisingly \(\color{blue}{\text{unstable}}\). The methods that we consider in this section do not suffer from this problem.

    • If the distribution of the predictors \(X\) is approximately normal in each of the classes and the sample size is small, then the approaches in this section may be more accurate than logistic regression.(If \(n\) is small and the distribution of the predictors \(X\) is approximately normal in each of the classes,LDA is again more stable than the logistic model.)

    • As mentioned in last page, linear discriminant analysis is popular when we have more than two response classes.

  • Using Bayes’ Theorem for Classification
    • Rules of multiplication \[P(A\cap B)=P(A)P(B|A=P(B)P(A|B))\]
    • Bayes’ Thm \({A_1,...,A_n}\) is a partition of the sample space (\(\Omega\)) \(P(A_i|B)=\frac{P(A_i)P(B|A_i)}{\sum _{j=1} ^{n} {P(A_j)P(B|A_j)}}\)
    • Let \(\pi _k\) represent the overall or prior probability that a randomly chosen observation comes from the \(k\)th class; this is the probability that a given observation is associated with the \(k\)th category of the response variable \(Y\). Let \(f_k(x)=P(X=x|Y=k)\) denote the density function of X for an observation that comes from the \(k\)th class. In other words, \(f_k(x)\) is relatively large if there is a high probability that an observation in the \(k\)th class has \(X ≈ x\). The Bayes Thm states that \[P(X=x|Y=k)=\frac{\pi_k f_k(x)}{\sum_{l=1}^{k} {\pi_l}{f_l(x)}}\]

we will use the abbreviation \(P_k(x)=P(Y=k|X=x)\). In general, estimating \(π_k\) is easy if we have a random sample of \(Y\) s from the population: we simply compute the fraction of the training observations that belong to the \(k\)th class. However, estimating \(f_k(X)\) tends to be more challenging, unless we assume some simple forms for these densities. We refer to \(p_k(x)\) as \(\color{blue}{\text{the posterior prob}}\) that an observation \(X = x\) belongs to the \(k\)thclass. That is, it is the probability that the observation belongs to the \(k\)th class, given the predictor value for that observation.

ex:
n=100, 25 obs from 1st class \(\pi_k\)
\(\Rightarrow \hat\pi_1=\frac{25}{100}\)

# Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){
  cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
  return(cormat)
}
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)
